Here's the registration:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient setup — one instance for the app's lifetime
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // Data service — singleton so every consumer shares the same
        // instance (and the same HttpClient / cache / auth state)
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so they bind to a fresh ViewModel each time
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

### Why each lifetime?

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reusing one instance avoids socket exhaustion. In production, swap for `AddHttpClient<IDataService>()` via `IHttpClientFactory` for even better control. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | It wraps `HttpClient` and may hold auth tokens or an in-memory cache. A single shared instance keeps that state consistent app-wide. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Each page navigation should start with clean VM state (no stale data from a previous visit). |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Pages are paired 1-to-1 with their ViewModel. A fresh page gets a fresh VM injected, avoiding state leaks between navigations. |

**Key rule of thumb:** services that hold shared resources or expensive connections → **Singleton**. UI-layer objects (pages, ViewModels) that should reset per navigation → **Transient**. Use **Scoped** only if you have a defined scope (e.g., a multi-step wizard sharing state across its child pages but resetting when re-entered).
